      "content": "One systematic approach to track down the memory leak is to use imperialine (or manual) leak detection. Here's a step-by-step guide:\n\n1. Implement a custom memory leak detector using a variable that keeps track of allocated memory blocks. You can use a static `int` to store the number of allocated blocks, and increment it each time `new` is called. Introduce a similar variable for deallocations by incrementing the logged allocation count when `delete` is called.\n\n2. Keep track of the logged data and correlate it with the time elapsed during steady state operation. Since the leak appears only after 4 or 5 hours, you may be able to identify a peak memory usage time frame.\n\n3. Locate specific data structures and call the memory leak detector function after each data structure constructionressing activity, such as `process_sensor_data`. Output the current memory usage to the console each time you compile and run, and look for areas that consistently leak memory.\n\n4. Use your valuable observation and picking pointers from memory logs and stability board data to Dude the slow process.",
